PLANT POISONING, OVINE - AUSTRALIA: (WESTERN AUSTRALIA) SWAINSONA
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 19 May 2014
Source: Highlight Press [edited]
http://www.highlightpress.com/australia-rocked-by-wave-of-sheep-suicides-vet-likens-outbreak-to-heroin-addiction/17191/ed-jones


Western Australia has been blighted with a spate of apparent sheep suicides, after a sizeable flocked grazed on a plant that proved to be both addictive and deadly. According to the Sydney Morning Herald, no less than 800 sheep are now known to have consumed the poisonous darling pea, with the plant having appeared across various pastures in the wake of heavy bushfires.

A leading veterinarian for the region likened the incident to a mass outbreak of class-A drug addiction. "It's like dealing with a thousand heroin addicts," said Bob McKinnon of North West Local Land Services, while speaking to the Herald. "They lose weight to start with and then get staggery, the progression gets worse, they get uncoordinated and depressed, they don't know where their feet are."

Many of the sheep tragically ended their own lives by repeatedly banging their heads into anything solid in the nearby vicinity, Mr McKinnon reported. Farmers and agricultural experts have since stepped up efforts to locate and destroy any remaining darling pea plants.

[byline: Ed Jones]

